-- Guided Childhood — Migration 076
-- Lesson library fill: 15 new Rosenshine format family lessons extending the
-- five exemplars in 074, so every stage covers its age appropriate literacy
-- strands. Foundation and Builder complete safe plus balance with an extra
-- lesson each. Explorer, Shaper and Independent gain the three strands 074
-- did not give them, so all four strands are covered from Explorer up.
-- Grounded in the UK Education for a Connected World framework, Catherine
-- Knibbs (nervous system and safety lens) and Dr Becky Kennedy (connection
-- first, telling is always safe). Difficulty rises with stage: two option
-- choices at Foundation, three at Builder, four with subtle distractors from
-- Explorer up. No dashes in any copy.
--
-- Idempotent: each insert is guarded by title, so this can run twice with no
-- duplicates. Dashboard safe: flat statements, dollar quoted JSON.

set lock_timeout = '3s';

-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- STAGE 1 · FOUNDATION (4 to 7)
-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- ── Foundation · Healthy balance ─────────────────────────────────────────────
insert into public.lessons (stage_id, audience, category, title, the_idea, why_it_matters, try_this, key_message, digi_prompt, sort_order, status, slides)
select 'foundation', 'parent', 'screen_habits', 'When the screen goes to sleep',
  'Little children do not end screen time, the ritual ends it for them. A gentle warning, a goodbye to the screen and a next thing to run to turn the hardest moment of the day into a routine.',
  'At 4 to 7 the thinking brain that manages stopping is still under construction. Every calm ending rehearsed now is a deposit in the skill they will need when the stakes are bigger.',
  'Give a five minute whisper before the end, let your child wave goodbye to the screen, and have the next thing ready: a snack, a job, a game. The goodbye does the heavy lifting.',
  'Warn, wave goodbye, move on to the next thing.',
  'How do I end screen time for my 5 year old without tears?',
  960, 'live',
  $f1$[
    {"type":"title","phase":"starter","minutes":1,"eyebrow":"Foundation · Ages 4 to 7 · Healthy balance","title":"When the screen goes to sleep","body":"A sofa lesson about endings. We practise saying goodbye to the screen so the goodbye stops being scary.","script":"Recall first: what is our stop and tell rule? Stop, and tell a grown up. Today is a different kind of goodbye: how we say bye bye to the screen when it is time."},
    {"type":"objective","phase":"starter","minutes":1,"outcome":"I can say goodbye to the screen calmly when my grown up gives the whisper.","why":"Endings feel big when they are a surprise. Our plan makes the ending small: a whisper, a wave, a next thing.","gains":["I know what the five minute whisper means","I can wave goodbye to the screen","I know the next thing comes straight after"]},
    {"type":"concept","phase":"teach","minutes":2,"emoji":"📣","heading":"The five minute whisper","body":"Big feelings come when the screen stops suddenly. So we never stop suddenly. Your grown up gives a quiet whisper: five more minutes. Your body gets time to get ready for the ending.","script":"Do the whisper the same way every time, low and warm, never a warning shot. This is the Dr Becky framing: you are not taking something away, you are walking them to the ending so they never meet it alone."},
    {"type":"concept","phase":"teach","minutes":2,"emoji":"👋","heading":"Wave goodbye, then run to the next thing","body":"When time is up, we wave and say bye bye screen, see you tomorrow. Then we go straight to the next thing: a snack, a story, a job helping your grown up. Endings are easier when something nice is waiting.","script":"The wave sounds silly and works like magic: it gives the ending a shape. Have the next thing genuinely ready before the wave happens. A child running toward something is not fighting what they left."},
    {"type":"choice","phase":"practise","minutes":2,"question":"The whisper has happened and now the timer says the screen is done. What do we do?","options":[{"text":"Wave bye bye to the screen and go to the next thing","correct":true,"feedback":"Yes. The wave finishes it, and the next thing is waiting for you."},{"text":"Hold the screen tight and look away from your grown up","correct":false,"feedback":"Holding tight makes the goodbye bigger and slower. The wave makes it small and quick."}]},
    {"type":"choice","phase":"prove","minutes":2,"question":"Why does the five minute whisper help your body?","options":[{"text":"It gives my body time to get ready for the ending","correct":true,"feedback":"Exactly. No surprise, no storm. Your body had time to get ready."},{"text":"It means I get extra screen time","correct":false,"feedback":"The whisper is not extra time. It is a kind warning that the ending is coming."}]},
    {"type":"digi","phase":"close","minutes":1,"heading":"DiGi says","lines":["A whisper, a wave, a next thing.","Endings are easier when nothing is a surprise.","Bye bye screen, see you tomorrow."]}
  ]$f1$::jsonb
where not exists (select 1 from public.lessons where title = 'When the screen goes to sleep');

-- ── Foundation · Safe online (extra) ─────────────────────────────────────────
insert into public.lessons (stage_id, audience, category, title, the_idea, why_it_matters, try_this, key_message, digi_prompt, sort_order, status, slides)
select 'foundation', 'parent', 'safety', 'Who is behind the screen',
  'Games and videos are full of people your child has never met. The lesson at this age is simple: screen people are strangers, we keep our special information private, and if anyone talks to us we come and show a grown up.',
  'Young children assume a friendly voice is a friend. The Education for a Connected World framework starts online relationships here: knowing that people online may not be who they say they are.',
  'Play the who knows you game: who knows your name? Grandma, your teacher, your friends. Does the person in the game know you? No. So we do not tell them our name.',
  'Screen people are strangers. Come and show me if anyone talks to you.',
  'How do I explain online strangers to a 6 year old without frightening them?',
  961, 'live',
  $f2$[
    {"type":"title","phase":"starter","minutes":1,"eyebrow":"Foundation · Ages 4 to 7 · Safe online","title":"Who is behind the screen","body":"A sofa lesson about the people inside games and videos, and what we keep just for the people we really know.","script":"Recall: what does your tummy do when something feels wrong on a screen? It gives you the funny feeling, and we stop and tell. Today we learn about the people on the other side of the screen."},
    {"type":"objective","phase":"starter","minutes":1,"outcome":"I can keep my special information private and show my grown up if anyone talks to me online.","why":"People in games can sound like friends. Knowing who really knows us keeps our special information safe.","gains":["I know screen people are strangers","I know what my special information is","I know to come and show my grown up"]},
    {"type":"concept","phase":"teach","minutes":2,"emoji":"🧸","heading":"Friendly is not the same as known","body":"People in games and videos can sound kind and funny. But we have never met them. They are strangers, even when they feel like friends. Strangers do not get our name, our school or where we live.","script":"Keep the tone light, not scary. Knibbs is clear that fear shuts learning down. The message is not that people online are bad. It is simply: we do not know them, so we keep our special information for people we know in real life."},
    {"type":"concept","phase":"teach","minutes":2,"emoji":"🫱","heading":"Come and show me","body":"If anyone in a game or an app says hello, asks a question or wants to be your friend, you do not have to answer. You come and show your grown up. Showing is always safe, and you will never be in trouble.","script":"This is the stop and tell rule wearing new clothes. Same promise, said slowly: whoever it is, whatever they said, showing me is always the right move, and I will always be glad you did."},
    {"type":"choice","phase":"practise","minutes":2,"question":"Someone in your game says: hi! What is your name? What do you do?","options":[{"text":"Tell them, because they sound friendly","correct":false,"feedback":"Friendly voices can still be strangers. Our name is special information for people we know in real life."},{"text":"Do not answer, and go and show your grown up","correct":true,"feedback":"Perfect. You do not have to answer anyone. Showing your grown up is always the right move."}]},
    {"type":"choice","phase":"prove","minutes":2,"question":"You showed your grown up a message from a stranger. What happens next?","options":[{"text":"They are glad you showed them, and they help","correct":true,"feedback":"Exactly. Showing is always safe in this family, and helping is our job."},{"text":"You lose the game as a punishment","correct":false,"feedback":"Never. Showing us never costs you the game. That promise is what keeps you safe."}]},
    {"type":"digi","phase":"close","minutes":1,"heading":"DiGi says","lines":["Screen people are strangers, even friendly ones.","Your name and your home are special information.","Come and show me. Showing is always safe."]}
  ]$f2$::jsonb
where not exists (select 1 from public.lessons where title = 'Who is behind the screen');

-- ── Foundation · Healthy balance (extra) ─────────────────────────────────────
insert into public.lessons (stage_id, audience, category, title, the_idea, why_it_matters, try_this, key_message, digi_prompt, sort_order, status, slides)
select 'foundation', 'parent', 'wellbeing', 'Big feelings and the screen',
  'Screens stir up big feelings in small bodies: fizzy, cross, wobbly. This lesson gives those feelings names, because a feeling with a name is a feeling a child can hand to you.',
  'Catherine Knibbs puts the nervous system at the centre: children do not calm down by being told to, they calm down next to a calm adult. Naming feelings together is the practice run.',
  'After screen time today, ask: how does your body feel, fizzy, wobbly or calm? No lesson attached, just the question. You are building the habit of noticing together.',
  'Every feeling is allowed. Naming it is how we tame it.',
  'My young child comes off the tablet cross and wobbly. What is going on and what do I do?',
  962, 'live',
  $f3$[
    {"type":"title","phase":"starter","minutes":1,"eyebrow":"Foundation · Ages 4 to 7 · Healthy balance","title":"Big feelings and the screen","body":"A sofa lesson about the feelings screens leave behind, and what we do with them together.","script":"Recall: what do we do when the screen goes to sleep? A whisper, a wave, a next thing. Today we talk about the feelings that sometimes arrive after the wave."},
    {"type":"objective","phase":"starter","minutes":1,"outcome":"I can name how my body feels after screens and bring big feelings to my grown up.","why":"Feelings are easier to handle when they have names and a helper.","gains":["I know fizzy, wobbly and calm","I know every feeling is allowed","I know where to bring a big feeling"]},
    {"type":"concept","phase":"teach","minutes":2,"emoji":"🌊","heading":"Fizzy, wobbly, calm","body":"Screens can make your body feel fizzy like a shaken bottle, or wobbly like jelly, or lovely and calm. All of those are allowed. Feelings are visitors. They come, we name them, and they go.","script":"Give the three words a home: fizzy for revved up, wobbly for upset, calm for settled. Children cannot say I am dysregulated, but every 5 year old can say I feel fizzy. That word is a gift to both of you."},
    {"type":"concept","phase":"teach","minutes":2,"emoji":"🤝","heading":"Bring the feeling to me","body":"When a big feeling comes after screens, you do not have to fix it on your own. Bring it to your grown up: I feel fizzy. Sitting close to a calm grown up helps your body find calm again. That is how bodies work.","script":"This is Knibbs made practical: children borrow our calm before they can build their own. So the deal is on you too. Take the breath first, then receive the feeling. A fizzy child plus a fizzy adult is just a bigger bottle of fizz."},
    {"type":"choice","phase":"practise","minutes":2,"question":"The tablet is away and your body feels like a shaken fizzy bottle. What do you do with that feeling?","options":[{"text":"Bring it to your grown up and say: I feel fizzy","correct":true,"feedback":"Yes. A named feeling is halfway to a calm one, and calm is easier next to your grown up."},{"text":"Hide it, because cross feelings are naughty","correct":false,"feedback":"No feeling is naughty. Every feeling is allowed, and bringing it to us is always right."}]},
    {"type":"choice","phase":"prove","minutes":2,"question":"What helps a wobbly body find calm again?","options":[{"text":"Being told to calm down right now","correct":false,"feedback":"Bodies do not calm down on command. They calm down next to someone calm."},{"text":"Sitting close to a calm grown up","correct":true,"feedback":"Exactly. Little bodies borrow calm from big ones. That is how it works."}]},
    {"type":"digi","phase":"close","minutes":1,"heading":"DiGi says","lines":["Fizzy, wobbly or calm, every feeling is allowed.","A named feeling is a tamed feeling.","Bring your feelings to your grown up, always."]}
  ]$f3$::jsonb
where not exists (select 1 from public.lessons where title = 'Big feelings and the screen');

-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- STAGE 2 · BUILDER (8 to 10)
